            <div class="text-center mb-12">
                <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-900 sm:text-4xl">The Current Legal Imperative for AGI Governance</h2>
                <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-8 text-slate-600 max-w-3xl mx-auto">This book proposal argues that the legal and regulatory frameworks for Artificial General Intelligence (AGI) must be built *before* it arrives. Waiting for its emergence would be too late. The central thesis is that proactive, anticipatory governance is not just prudent, but essential to steer this transformative technology towards a safe and equitable future.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-sm border border-slate-200">
                    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900">Epistemic Shift</h3>
                    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">AGI may operate on principles like quantum or probabilistic reasoning, fundamentally challenging classical legal concepts of intent, foreseeability, and causality.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-sm border border-slate-200">
                    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900">Shared Infrastructure</h3>
                    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">The book reframes AGI not as private property but as a "shared epistemic infrastructure"‚Äîa global public good that demands collective stewardship, not corporate enclosure.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-sm border border-slate-200">
                    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900">Moderate Regulation</h3>
                    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">The goal is to find a balance between "technopanic and laissez-faire optimism," creating guardrails that enable safe progress rather than blockades that stifle innovation.</p>
